entry.title: [gnrt] Skip bin targets by default (with opt-in via gnrt_config.toml).
entry.content:
This CL is motivated by the desire to address the second requirement

below, while making sure that the first requirement doesn't regress:



* Requirement 1: `gnrt gen` needs to generate `BUILD.gn` targets for

_some_ binary targets. Currently this is required only for a single

target: `cxxbridge`.



* Requirement 2: All generated `BUILD.gn` targets should build. Before

this CL this requirement wouldn't hold for some binary targets - for

example the `uwuifier` target from the Chromium section of the

Comprehensive Rust course would fail to build - see

https://crbug.com/1509606.



This CL skips binary targets by default, because:



* This helps to address the second requirement above

* Transitive dependencies only follow the library targets (i.e. skipping

binary targets should not introduce dangling dependencies)

* Binary targets seem to be needed rarely in practice



This CL adds a new `gnrt_config.toml` entry that allows an opt-in for

coverinng binary targets when needed. This helps to address the first

requirement above.



This CL also introduces the `BuildConfig::get_combined_set` method to

avoid duplication of code related to processing

`CrateConfig::bin_targets` (introduced in this CL) and

`CrateConfig::remove_deps` (already exists before this CL).

entry.title: [iOS] Remove last use of PasswordFetcher
entry.content:
PasswordFetcher was making unnecessary requests to the password stores

and was duplicating work that was already done by other classes. In an

effort to remove this unnecessary class, this CL removes the last use of

PasswordFetcher in the ManualFillPasswordMediator and instead uses the

PasswordManager to fetch passwords related to a specific form and the

SavedPasswordsPresenter to fetch all saved passwords.



Specifically, this CL:

- Exposes a getter method in FormInputAccessoryMediator so that

FormInputAccessoryCoordinator can access and use the `lastSeenParams` to

then pass the form and frame IDs all the way to the

ManualFillPasswordMediator. ManualFillPasswordMediator can then use

those IDs to fetch the passwords that are related to the current form.



- Creates an instance of SavedPasswordsPresenter in

ManualFillAllPasswordCoordinator so that is can be used by the

ManualFillPasswordMediator to fetch all saved passwords.



- Fixes and improves PasswordViewController EG tests.



- Adds unit tests to make sure that the ManualFillPasswordMediator

notifies its consumer when passwords are fetched.



- Deletes files that are now unused.

entry.title: WebUI: Remove "useDefineForClassFields" from default TS config, part1.
entry.content:
In this part, adding "useDefineForClassFields: false" to all places that

need it, but not removing it from the default TS config yet, to reduce

the chances of the bulk of the work to be reverted. Will be removed in a

follow-up.



This flag should be turned off only in UIs that have a good reason to do

so. More specifically:

- UIs that use Polymer properties (moved flag to

tsconfig_base_polymer.json),

since Polymer's property definitions are not compatible with it.

- UIs that can't handle newer JS code (meaning code adhering to latest

ECMAScript standards), like c/b/r/chromeos/desk_api which feeds

Typescript's output to the Closure compiler (via js_binary() calls).

- UIs that use Lit with legacy decorators (ui/file_manager,

third_party/cros-componens)



Motivation for this change is to not have the default TS configuration

unnecessarily block the possibility of using Lit's standard JS decorators,

which requires using "useDefineForClassFields: true" (see [1]), in the

context of the ongoing Lit experimentation.



[1] https://lit.dev/docs/components/decorators/#migrating-typescript-standard-decorators

entry.title: Allow rp overlay backing to be shrunk by rp->output_rect
entry.content:
This clipping was removed from CalculateRPDQParams() in CL[1]

because the work was redundant for non-overlaid RPs (work repeated in

Skia). But it was added back to PrepareRenderPassOverlay() in CL[2] so

that RP overlay backings can be allocated at smaller sizes. However one case from before CL[1] was missed.



If an rpdq has no clip_rect, it could still be clipped by the root RP's

output_rect as a default. That means we should always set the inverse

transform when possible so we can transform any clip_rect into the

RPDQ's space.



I've confirmed locally with the visual debugger in Lacros that this

reduces the filter bounds after applying clipping.

entry.title: [Privacy Sandbox] Do not convert attestation list directory using
entry.content:
AsUTF8Unsafe().



From histograms, we found there is a Windows specific issue that the

std::ifstream fails to open. I tested the existing implementation and

found it fails to open the file when the directory contains combining

characters, for example "√Ö" and "√∂". See crrev.com/c/5089910 for the

try bot failures.



I realize that the converted directory returned by

`base::FilePath::AsUTF8Unsafe()` is not guaranteed to work across

platforms. We should stick to `base::FilePath`.



Changed to `ReadFileToString`, then `ParseFromString`. It seems most

existing proto parsing implementation in Chromium is done this way.



Although there is no crash reports that we can use to investigate if

the combining character is actually the root cause, this is a fix we

should make.

entry.title: Fix dangling ptr in IndexedDBTestFirstOrThirdParty
entry.content:
A helper object, LevelDBLock, stored a pointer to a leveldb::FileLock

that was returned from a call to LockFile. The pointer represented

ownership of the FileLock and was freed later during a call to

UnlockFile. However, the pointer wasn't being cleared as part of that

call, leading to the dangling pointer warning.



This CL updates LevelDBLock to use std::unique_ptr instead of a raw_ptr

for holding the FileLock pointer. This avoids both the dangling pointer

issue and helps ensure any future use of LevelDBLock will understand

the ownership contract that was previously present, but unstated.

Canvas filters are defined as following the SVG specification, so

we must support distinct X and Y blur std-deviations.
